node.text:
#HelloWorld.

‚ÄúMy work is simply to be enjoyed. I considered it escapism, something to indulge in and forget about the bullsh*t.‚Äù Alec West‚Äôs (@alec.fbx) colorful lo-fi renderings throw back to gaming‚Äôs early years. ‚ÄúI make animations that mainly just capture a moment in an ever-growing world, each video being another piece in the puzzle. All my life I have been creating art. In middle school, I would go on websites and watch pivot stick fighter animations all day. I would attempt my own crude versions at home downloading pre-made assets.‚Äù

Alec developed his pixelated world and original character Tri-Tails using free open-source software. ‚ÄúThe work that took a team of 40-plus people 20 years ago, I can do in my room alone today. I am excited to see where these tools will take us and what will be made. I am in a server with extremely talented artists, ranging across many different forms of digital art and software. I don‚Äôt know what I would do without this community. Having people to reach out to for help and just general questions is something I won‚Äôt ever take for granted. This is something anyone should be able to do if they want. It‚Äôs our goal to not only inspire but help them achieve that goal.‚Äù

Video by @alec.fbx
Music by @goreshit.sucks

node.text:
‚ÄúI like to bottle up auras only I can see, in the hopes other people can see them too,‚Äù says Nat ƒÜmiel, the visual artist and musician who is manifesting the otherworldly, ethereal enigma that is yeule (@yeule).

‚ÄúThe yeule project is a sonic and visual time capsule that snapshots eras of my shape-shifting self and the experience of pathos. Musically, yeule lies somewhere between electronic nu-pop cy-earth music II and indie confessional emo.‚Äù Born in Singapore and based in London, the self-styled ‚Äúglitch princess‚Äù was a quiet and introverted child before finding their sense of belonging online ‚Äî drawing inspiration for yeule from the cyber dimension. ‚ÄúAs a Singaporean artist, I feel proud of representing Southeast Asia in the electronic music scene. I stand for mental health awareness, trans rights and dedicate my work on this earth to the friends I lost, who couldn‚Äôt be seen the way they wanted to be.

I want to hit that spot where it hurts so bad and burns so hot, but you can never take a picture or show anyone what it looked like. Songwriting starts from the dreams and memories that scar the most and end up in my journal in crumpled pieces of paper. I hope it sounds pretty, even though the contents are decaying inside. I won‚Äôt sing something I don‚Äôt mean, and I don‚Äôt play something I don‚Äôt really like. There must be a reason why I chip at this concrete so meticulously, right? To make it look as close as it can to what I have seen with my own eyes.‚Äù

Video by @yeule

node.text:
Artist Jon Batiste (@jonbatiste) is a whole vibe. üé∂ He‚Äôs heading to the Grammy Awards (@recordingacademy) with 11 different nominations ‚Äî the most of any nominee this year. ü§Øüëè

But before Jon‚Äôs performance at the awards, he met up with friends in New York City for one of his self-proclaimed ‚Äúlove riots.‚Äù

‚ÄúLove riots are like chaotic, fun, impromptu musical parades. It started as something I would do in transit from one place to the next, whether on the way to the recording studio or to rehearsal or even just to the market,‚Äù says Jon. ‚ÄúIt borrows from the second-line tradition of my hometown New Orleans, typically starting with a few people and gathering folks along the way. I love the feeling of ceremony and sense of community that it brings.‚Äù

Meet Jon‚Äôs community and hear his soulful sound from the subway to the studio before tonight‚Äôs show in Las Vegas.

ü§çüè≥Ô∏è‚Äç‚ößÔ∏è ‚ÄúGrowing up, I never really saw anyone who truly represented me in mainstream media. Trans Day of Visibility is important because it reminds trans people that they are not alone. There are so many people within our community who are making the world a better place. This day represents being bold and thriving in a world that is not always the most welcoming or safe for us.‚Äù ‚ÄîWriter and creator Devin Halbal (@devinhalbal)

Video by @devinhalbal

node.text:
For ceramicist Lisa Asano (@lisa_asano), every new vessel is a new journey. The creation process, the final product and what happens to a piece once it‚Äôs in someone‚Äôs hands ‚Äî every step along its way is one worth celebrating.

‚ÄúBlack joy to me is just the most contagious joy. I feel like it‚Äôs the most fulfilling and happiest joy that you could ever feel. I‚Äôm lucky to say that I‚Äôm able to experience that type of joy in my life.‚Äù

This Black History Month, we‚Äôre continuing to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory.

Video by @lisa_asano

node.text:
Yasmeen ‚ÄúYaz‚Äù Wilkerson (@yaz.so.mean) surfs and skateboards around the world, spreading joy wherever she travels.

‚ÄúWhat do I love about these sports? Everything. I love the way they make me feel. The lessons and teachings that I‚Äôve learned in skateboarding and surfing, I definitely take and use in my daily life ‚Äî whether it‚Äôs the art of determination, expression or how to communicate not only with other people, but with yourself.‚Äù

This Black History Month, we‚Äôre continuing to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory.

node.text:
üí¶ Rub-a-dub-dub,
one cat in the tub! üí¶

Meet Winnie (@showeringkitty), a 5-year-old rescue tabby who goes with the flow. ‚ÄúWinnie loves to go into the tub and under the faucet or showerhead,‚Äù says her human Enza. ‚ÄúShe does this first thing in the morning and calls for me to come and turn on the water, often while I‚Äôm still in bed.‚Äù üòÇ

Video by @showeringkitty

node.accessibility_caption: Digital art of a person with large blue eyes and their hands resting on their chin.

node.text:
‚ÄúWhen I stare into their expressions and wonder why I felt the need to paint them that way, sometimes I feel that my paintings understand me better than myself.‚Äù Korean American freelance illustrator @jisuartist (Jisu) incorporates a heavy emphasis on advanced digital painting technique, as well as CG design elements in her work, bringing a fresh take to relatable themes. ‚ÄúA lot of my work masquerades dark themes with bright, saccharine colors. The characters you see in my work are definitely a reflection of me. They express the thoughts and feelings I have at that present time ‚Äî many of which revolve around my mental health.

The most important thing to me as an individual and as an artist is being authentic. I grew up feeling very judged and boxed in due to my conservative upbringing, and in turn expressed my true self through my art. In my teens, my art went semi-viral within the fan art communities and kickstarted my career, but over time, being known for one thing pigeon-holed me into yet another box. I felt a disconnect between my work and my true self again.‚Äù

After taking a year off, Jisu felt able to express herself again. ‚ÄúNFTs have made it so that you as a creative no longer have to tailor yourself to the masses for their patronage, and instead can indulge in creating for only a few dedicated collectors. This shift has enabled artists like me to finally create what we want, how we want and be compensated for it.‚Äù

Art by @jisuartist

node.accessibility_caption: A person with pink and black hair stands on a stairway above a city street.

node.text:
Like an anime character. üíñ 
 
Wednesday Campanella‚Äôs new vocalist @utaha.89‚Äôs (Utaha) signature ponytails, piercings and positive energy make her a ready-made focal point for the iconic Japanese band. 
 
In 2021, when founding vocalist KOM_I left Wednesday Campanella to pursue solo projects, band member Dir.F slid into Utaha‚Äôs DMs to recruit her to join him and Kenmochi Hidefumi in the unique three-member J-pop unit known for blending genres and their clever word play. The new EP ‚ÄúNeon‚Äù marks Utaha‚Äôs recorded debut as a vocalist with the band. 
 
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs been less than a year since I‚Äôve taken over as the second generation, but I am already going across Japan, playing in live shows and improving my performance,‚Äù says the 20-year-old artist. ‚ÄúAt first, I was a little worried, but after the first release, I received more support and cheers than I could have imagined. I want to tell everyone about self-affirmation and love by playing music on stage in front of people. I hope that, by being the artist I am, I will be able to convey the fact that someone‚Äôs identity is wonderful, no matter how they look.‚Äù 
 
Photo of @utaha.89 by @ikenoshiori; video and photo by @utaha.89

Reel by @yanismofficial

#HelloWorld

‚ÄúI like making artwork that 12-year-old me would freak over.‚Äù ‚Äî@lordstingray (Nam Mac)

‚ÄúI‚Äôm drawn to the simplicity of retro games‚Äô visual style because it emphasizes the design choices made within every element of the scene and allows for a large amount of creative freedom,‚Äù says the artist, who arrived at the lo-fi and pixelated computer-generated work he makes today via traditional illustration.

‚ÄúMy artwork is simply a window. It‚Äôs a way for others to see the things I see. The worlds I build are a melting pot of all my interests growing up, like cartoons, video games and anime. Taking this visual inspiration and combining it with my day-to-day life is what drives my work. The stories in my animations are little moments and thoughts expressed in a visual format in the simplest way possible. The first priority is to think about what feeling to create. From there it‚Äôs just about researching the tools to make what you see in your head.

Keep it fun and you‚Äôll make your best stuff.‚Äù

Videos by @lordstingray 
Music by @perfectchao, @kyotopill and @perfectchao

node.text:
‚ÄúI‚Äôm motivated by the idea of making someone smile on a rough day and making some bad day just a little less bad.‚Äù ‚Äî@realliamsilk (Liam Silk)

Liam‚Äôs relatable comedy videos are mostly based on real-life experiences with friends and family. ‚ÄúThe themes to my work are very uplifting and generally upbeat ideas or topics. There is a lot of ugly in the world and I want to do anything I can to make the world just a little brighter,‚Äù says Liam, who started posting his videos during his freshman year of high school. ‚ÄúMy work seeks to challenge the notion that to be funny you must be vulgar or bring someone down. I think comedy should be exponentially positive and shouldn‚Äôt come at the cost of someone‚Äôs feelings.‚Äù

Photo by @realliamsilk

node.text:
Digital painter @ram__han‚Äôs (Ram Han) ethereal dreamscapes are centered in nostalgia and fantasy, surrealism and the ambiguity of human memory.

‚ÄúI like to draw images found in everyday memories and images encountered through the media by mixing them into one worldview. As an artist in a position to create digital artwork, I want my paintings to be reminiscent of tactile stimulation as well as visual stimulation,‚Äù says Ram, who has described her work as visual ASMR.

Ram integrates elements like flowers, animals, abstract forms and textures to extend her work‚Äôs symbolic meaning and provide sensation and pleasure.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs impossible for everything I‚Äôve been affected by to be harmless and moral. Because the world wasn‚Äôt made that way. The goal of the narrative in my pieces is owning the memory of place or experience that the viewers never had.

My work can give you a familiar feeling. Whatever it is, I want people to gain a uniquely personal experience through my art.‚Äù

Art by @ram__han
